meta {
  title = MCP Server,
  order = 3,
  icon = server
}

Tiramisu Docs includes a built-in MCP (Model Context Protocol) server that allows AI assistants like Claude\, Cursor\, and other MCP-compatible tools to browse your documentation programmatically.

The server is hosted as an HTTP JSON-RPC endpoint at code { /mcp } on your deployed docs site. It ships as a SvelteKit route — no CLI\, no separate process\, no local setup. Deploy your site and the MCP server is live.

h2 { Enabling the Server }

Set code { mcp: true } in your config to generate a code { /mcp } POST route and show "Connect" buttons in your docs UI:

codeblock { language = typescript, """import { defineConfig } from "@tiramisu-docs/kit";

export default defineConfig({
  mcp: true,
  // ...
});""" }

When enabled\, this does two things:

list {
  Generates a code { /mcp } POST route that handles JSON-RPC 2.0 requests from AI tools,
  Shows bold { Connect with MCP } and bold { Connect to VSCode } buttons on your docs pages — the URL is derived automatically from your site's origin
}

h2 { Custom Server URL }

If you host your MCP server separately or want the UI buttons to point to a different endpoint\, pass a URL string instead:

codeblock { language = typescript, """export default defineConfig({
  mcp: "https://docs.example.com/mcp",
  // ...
});""" }

When a string is provided:

list {
  The UI buttons point to the given URL,
  No code { /mcp } route is generated — you are responsible for hosting the server at that URL
}

h2 { Connecting AI Tools }

Once your site is deployed with code { mcp: true }\, AI tools can connect using the hosted URL.

h3 { Claude Code }

Add to your code { .mcp.json } file in the project root:

codeblock { language = json, """{
  "mcpServers": {
    "my-docs": {
      "type": "streamableHttp",
      "url": "https://docs.example.com/mcp"
    }
  }
}""" }

Replace code { docs.example.com } with your actual docs domain.

h3 { Cursor }

In Cursor's MCP settings\, add a new server and paste your docs MCP URL (e.g. code { https://docs.example.com/mcp }). Cursor supports HTTP MCP endpoints natively.

h3 { VSCode }

Your docs site shows a bold { Connect to VSCode } button in the Open dropdown. Clicking it uses the code { "vscode:mcp/install" } protocol handler to register the server automatically — no manual configuration needed.

h2 { Available Tools }

The server exposes five tools to AI assistants:

table {
  row = [bold { Tool }, bold { Description }],
  row = [code { search_docs }, Search pages by keyword],
  row = [code { read_doc }, Read a specific page by slug],
  row = [code { list_pages }, List all documentation pages\, optionally filtered by section],
  row = [code { list_sections }, List all sections with page counts],
  row = [code { get_table_of_contents }, Get headings for a specific page]
}

h2 { How It Works }

The MCP server is a standard SvelteKit POST route at code { /mcp }. It speaks JSON-RPC 2.0 over HTTP — each request is a single POST with a JSON body\, and the response is JSON.

Documentation data comes from the code { virtual:tiramisu-docs } module at build time. The server does not scan the filesystem at runtime\, which means it works on any deployment target: serverless functions\, edge runtimes\, static adapters with prerendering\, or traditional Node.js servers. Wherever SvelteKit runs\, the MCP server runs.

callout { type = info, Since the server is built into your site\, it stays in sync with your docs automatically. Every deploy updates both the documentation and the MCP endpoint. }
